{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488541"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:46:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:46:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"473"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/473"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.09,0.07,0.68,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92263"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/473"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75562"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"419"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9593"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42088"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92263"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of his diabetes. During the consultation, he mentions some painless scaly lesions on the backs of his hands that have been present for many months. He has a history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension. His medications include metformin and perindopril. He worked as a farmer for 40 years before retiring. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Multiple erythematous, scaly patches are visible on the dorsum of both hands, with one lesion showing signs of ulceration (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate topical treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clotrimazole cream","Triamcinolone cream","Miconazole cream","5-fluorouracil cream","Griseofulvin cream"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with actinic keratoses - scaly, erythematous patches on sun-exposed areas. His history of outdoor work and advanced age are significant risk factors. The presence of an ulcerated lesion raises concern for possible progression to squamous cell carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E5-fluorouracil\u003C/strong\u003E cream (brand name Efudix) is the most appropriate treatment for multiple actinic keratoses. Whilst cryotherapy would be helpful for a few lesions, when there are multiple actinic keratoses it is advisable to consider other treatment due to the pain.  5-Fluorouracil works by interfering with DNA synthesis in rapidly dividing cells and is particularly effective for treating areas with multiple lesions. Treatment typically continues for 2-4 weeks, though local irritation is common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClotrimazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal medication used to treat superficial fungal infections. It would not be effective against pre-malignant actinic keratoses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriamcinolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a topical corticosteroid used for inflammatory skin conditions. It would be inappropriate for actinic keratoses as it may mask progression to malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiconazole\u003C/strong\u003E, like clotrimazole, is an antifungal agent with no role in treating pre-malignant lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGriseofulvin\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used as an oral antifungal medication, not as a topical preparation. It would have no role in treating actinic keratoses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile treating with 5-fluorouracil, the patient should be advised about continual sun protection and the need for regular full-body skin checks. The ulcerated lesion should ideally be biopsied to exclude malignant transformation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Actinic keratoses are pre-malignant lesions that can progress to squamous cell carcinoma if left untreated","Topical 5-fluorouracil is an effective first-line treatment for multiple actinic keratoses","Regular skin checks are important in elderly patients with sun-damaged skin"],"references":["de Oliveira ECV, da Motta VRV, Pantoja PC, et al. Actinic keratosis - review for clinical practice. Int J Derm 2019; 58:400-07","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Arasu A, Meah N, Sinclair R. Skin checks in primary care [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practitioners. 2019: 48 (9) Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/september/skin-checks-in-primary-care"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75562"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"473"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18479"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18479"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3